The paper discusses the development of a mathematical schema theory that draws from brain theory schemas, grid automata, and block-shemas. This suggests that the paper may be relevant to several sub-categories in computer science. 

cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) is a likely sub-category as the paper discusses the use of mathematical tools to model schemas in various fields, including neurophisiology and psychology. 

cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) is also a likely sub-category as the paper draws from brain theory schemas and discusses the modeling of schemas in neurophisiology. 

cs.LG (Machine Learning) is a possible sub-category as the paper discusses the use of mathematical tools to model schemas in various fields, including computer science. 

cs.SY (Systems and Control) is a possible sub-category as the paper discusses the use of mathematical tools to model schemas in various fields, including databases and logic. 

cs.IT (Information Theory) is a possible sub-category as the paper discusses the use of mathematical tools to model schemas in Internet technology.
